Description:  ¶

Data Description: The actual concrete compressive strength (MPa) for a given mixture under a specific age (days) was determined from laboratory. Data is in raw form (not scaled).The data has 8 quantitative input variables, and 1 quantitative output variable, and 1030 instances (observations).¶

Domain: Material manufacturing¶

Context: Concrete is the most important material in civil engineering. The concrete compressive strength is a highly nonlinear function of age and ingredients. These ingredients include cement, blast furnace slag, fly ash, water, superplasticizer, coarse aggregate, and fine aggregate.¶

Attribute Information:¶

  • Cement : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
  • Blast : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
  • Fly ash : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
  • Water : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
  • Superplasticizer : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
  • Coarse Aggregate : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
  • Fine Aggregate : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
  • Age : day (1~365)
  • Concrete compressive strength measured in MPa

Learning Outcomes:¶

  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Building ML models for regression
  • Hyper parameter tuning

Objective: Modeling of strength of high performance concrete using Machine Learning¶

Steps and tasks:¶

1. Deliverable -1 (Exploratory data quality report reflecting the following)¶
a. Univariate analysis 
    i. Univariate analysis – data types and description of the independent attributes which should include (name, meaning, range of values observed, central values (mean and median), standard deviation and quartiles, analysis of the body of distributions / tails,  missing values, outliers 
b. Multivariate analysis  
    i. Bi-variate analysis between the predictor variables and between the predictor variables and target column. Comment on your findings in terms of their relationship and degree of relation if any. Presence of leverage points. Visualize the analysis using boxplots and pair plots, histograms or density curves. Select the most appropriate attributes 
c. Strategies to address the different data challenges such as data pollution, outliers and missing values
2. Deliverable -2 (Feature Engineering techniques)¶
a. Identify opportunities (if any) to create a composite feature, drop a feature 
b. Decide on complexity of the model, should it be simple linear mode in terms of parameters or would a quadratic or higher degree help 
c. Explore for gaussians. If data is likely to be a mix of gaussians, explore individual clusters and present your findings in terms of the independent attributes and their suitability to predict strength
3. Deliverable -3 (create the model )¶
a. Obtain feature importance for the individual features using multiple methods and present your findings
4. Deliverable -4 (Tuning the model)¶
a. Algorithms that you think will be suitable for this project 
b. Techniques employed to squeeze that extra performance out of the model without making it overfit or underfit 
c. Model performance range at 95% confidence level

Ridge Regression¶

In [23]:
ridge = Ridge(alpha=.3,random_state=1) #Ridge Regression
ridge.fit(X_train,y_train) #Fit
predicted_ridge = ridge.predict(X_test) #Predict 


T_rmse_ridge=np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_train,ridge.predict(X_train)))#Training mean squared error
Training_R2_ridge = r2_score(y_train,ridge.predict(X_train))#Training R2 score

RMSE_ridge=np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test,predicted_ridge))#Test mean squared error
R2_ridge=r2_score(y_test, predicted_ridge)#Test R2 score

Scores = [('Mean Absolute Error',mean_absolute_error(y_train,ridge.predict(X_train)),'Mean Absolute Error',mean_absolute_error(y_test,predicted_ridge)),
      ('Mean Squared Error',mean_squared_error(y_train,ridge.predict(X_train)),'Mean Squared Error',mean_squared_error(y_test,predicted_ridge)),
      ('Root Mean Squared Error',T_rmse_ridge,'Root Mean Squared Error',RMSE_ridge),
      ('R2 Score',Training_R2_ridge,'R2 Score',R2_ridge)] #List of accuracy scores of all models

Scores = pd.DataFrame(Scores,columns=['Train Data','Score','Test Data','Score'])

Comments on Models¶

  • Above Score are Sorted on the basis of R2 Test Score
  • Adjusted R2 scores are more effecient in eveluating goodness of fit. As there is not a builtin function to calculate adjusted R2, R2 scoring is used to assess the performance of models.
  • Along with R2, Root Mean Squared Error(RMSE), Mean Squared Error(MSE) and Mean Absolute Error(MAE) are used to assess the performance of model.
  • R2 Scores and RMSE are inversely proportional i.e. increase in R2 will reduce RMSE.
  • The scores are in ascending order.
  • The Linear regression techniques are producing 49% to 75% R2 score even with Polynomials. So non linear models are preferable for achieving the goal of prediction.
  • Gradient boosting,Random forest,Bagging and Decision tree regressor are performing well in terms of regression as these models are able to achieve R2 scores >=85%
  • Though these models are able to produce 85% score, these models are overfitting.
  • The model with lowest RMSE should be preferred. In this analysis it is Gradient Boosting Regressor.
  • Model comparison is shown below in line graph.

Bootstrapping at 95% confidence interval¶

  • Boostrapping will help in calculating how much variance is TRULY captured in 95% Confidence interval.
  • For evaluating the regressors, R2 Scores are used.

Gradient Boosting Regressor¶

In [37]:
import warnings
warnings.simplefilter(action='ignore', category=FutureWarning)

values=DataFrame_scaled.values
from sklearn.utils import resample
# configure bootstrap
n_iterations = 1000              # Number of bootstrap samples to create
n_size = int(len(DataFrame_scaled) * 0.50)    # picking only 50 % of the given data in every bootstrap sample

# run bootstrap
stats = list()
for i in range(n_iterations):
    # prepare train and test sets
    train = resample(values, n_samples=n_size)  # Sampling with replacement 
    test = np.array([x for x in values if x.tolist() not in train.tolist()])  # picking rest of the data not considered in sample
    # fit model
    model = GradientBoostingRegressor(alpha= 0.1, learning_rate= 0.1, max_depth= 4, max_features= 2, n_estimators=490,
                                random_state= 1)
    model.fit(train[:,:-1], train[:,-1])
    # evaluate model
    predictions = model.predict(test[:,:-1])
    score = r2_score(test[:,-1], predictions)    # caution, overall accuracy score can mislead when classes are imbalanced
    stats.append(score)
In [38]:
# plot scores
plt.hist(stats)
plt.show()
# confidence intervals
alpha = 0.95 # for 95% confidence 
p = ((1.0-alpha)/2.0) * 100 # tail regions on right and left .25 on each side indicated by P value (border)
lower = max(0.0, np.percentile(stats, p))  
p = (alpha+((1.0-alpha)/2.0)) * 100
upper = min(1.0, np.percentile(stats, p))
print('%.1f confidence interval %.1f%% and %.1f%%' % (alpha*100, lower*100, upper*100))

95.0 confidence interval 86.9% and 91.4%
  • On 95% Confidence Interval, Gradient Boosting Regressor is able to cover 86.6% to 91.5% variation

from sklearn.utils import resample
# configure bootstrap
n_iterations = 1000              # Number of bootstrap samples to create

# run bootstrap

for i in range(n_iterations):

After CrossValidation Comments:¶

  • All Previous Scores are from Section 6.
  • The Gradient Boosting regressor is able to produce around 93% R2 score than previous 90% i.e. 3% improved score is achieved after cross validation.
  • The Support Vector regressor is able to produce around 87% R2 score than previous 62% i.e. 25% improved score is achieved after cross validation.
  • The Decision Tree regressor is able to produce around 87% R2 score than previous 85% i.e. 2% improved score is achieved after cross validation.
  • The Random Forest regressor is able to produce around 82% R2 score than previous 90% i.e. 8% loss in score can be observed.
  • As Random Forest regressor is Cross Validated using RandomizedSearchCV, the obtained parameters may not be the best ones, as RandomizedSearchCV does not guarantee that it will produce best parameters.

Comments¶

  • All insights, important observation have alredy been added below every step. These are some concluding comments.

Comments on Dataset¶

  • All values in the dataset are continuous numerical values.
  • 4-5 Outliers are present in some columns,the number is less in proportion.
  • No missing values are detected in the dataset.

Comments on Models¶

  • At first, Linear Regression based models like OLS, Ridge and Lasso Regression techniqes are used for prediction.
  • The prediction task is not linearly solvable, and it is proved by poor performance of linear models.
  • Ensemble techniques proved to be good estimators.
  • The Overfitting of models is detected, but it is solved in some degree in CrossValidation steps.
  • The GridSearchCV produced more reliable hyperparameters than RandomizedSearchCV.
  • Bootstrapping of Higher performance model GradientBoostingRegressor captured 86.8% to 91.5% guaranteed r2 Score for this dataset.

Comments on Clusterwise models¶

  • The clusterwise models are able to provide more reliable results as the degree of overfitting is reduced in models and all models are producing more than 85% R2 score.
  • The 5 clusters are chosen by using quadratic error and also by analyzing pairplot density diagonal.
  • Bagging regressor, RandomForestRegressor and GradientBoosting Regressor proved tobe good in predicting the strength with R2 score more than 85%.

Miscellaneous Comments¶

  • Due to Bootstrapping and higher number of parameters in GridSearchCV and RandomizedSearchCV, the project takes time to execute.
  • Pairplot provided meaningful insights to decide number of cluster in kmeans.
  • GradientBoostingRegressor performed well on most of the dataset.
  • Due to lack of domain knowledge, at some instance, any pracitcally significant but stastically not significant feature might have been removed from the data;But all removed features are removed using DecisionTree Feature importance test.
